other heuristic that could be used for bin packing.\n\nBut since the function is to return a priority score for each bin, you can think of it as a scoring system that determines which bin is best suited for the next item.\n\nThe functions can be based on any of these heuristics or any other heuristic approach.\n\n### Suggested Scoring Functions:\n- **Fill Rate**: How full a bin is.\n- **Space Left**: How much space is left in a bin.\n- **Item Size vs Bin Size**: How well the item fits into the bin.\n- **Variance in Bin Sizes**: How uniform the bin sizes are.\n- **Other Metrics**: Any other metric that could help determine the best bin.\n\nEach function can combine these metrics in different ways to produce a unique priority score.\n\n### Final Note:\nEach function must be unique in the way it calculates the priority. Even minor differences in the mathematical operations or the use of different NumPy functions can make the implementation unique.\n\n---\n\n### Example Implementations (for reference, not to be used as is):\n\n1. def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n2. def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.sqrt(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * item / bins)\n\n3. def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.log(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n4. def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.std(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n5. def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.max(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n6. def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.min(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n7. def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.median(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n8. def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.var(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n9. def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.sum(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n10. def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.prod(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\nBut these are just examples. You need to create 10 unique implementations.\n\n---\n\n### Additional Suggestion:\nEach function can use a combination of different array operations and mathematical functions to create a unique scoring mechanism. For example, combining fill rate with the item size, or using a more complex formula that includes multiple operations.\n\nSo, for each function, try to think of a different way to combine the allowed operations to calculate the priority score.\n\n---\n\n### Final Instructions:\n- Each function must be correct, but not necessarily optimal.\n- All functions must return an array of the same shape as bins.\n- Each function must be unique in its combination of operations and logic.\n- Use a variety of NumPy functions and mathematical operations to ensure uniqueness.\n</think>\n\nHere are 10 unique implementations of the `priority` function:\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.sqrt(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * item / bins)\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.log(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float,