For example, one function could use the mean, another the median, another the mode, etc.\n\n### How to Generate the Functions:\n\nEach function will compute a priority score for each bin based on the current state of the bins and the item to be placed.\n\n### Your Task:\n\nCreate 10 unique functions, each using a different combination of allowed operations to compute the priority.\n\n### Constraints:\n\n- All functions must be vectorized and not use any loops or conditionals.\n- The functions must not use any print statements or external dependencies beyond numpy.\n- The functions must return an array of the same size as bins.\n\n### Sample Output Format:\n\nFor each function, you will provide the code in the format:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return [expression]\n\nBut without the comments.\n\n### How to Measure Loss:\n\nThe loss is computed as the total wasted space after packing all items. So, functions that lead to lower loss are better.\n\n### Notes:\n\nThe functions are heuristics, so they don't need to be optimal, just different.\n\n### Additional Notes:\n\nEach function is a heuristic, and the loss is just a measure of how good the heuristic is. The functions are not required to minimize the loss; they just need to compute a priority.\n\n### Starting Point:\n\nThe priority function should return an array where each element represents the priority of each bin for the item to be placed.\n\n### Instructions:\n\n1. Think about different ways to combine the allowed operations to compute a priority score.\n2. Each function must compute a unique priority heuristic.\n3. Use different combinations of mathematical operations, statistical functions, etc.\n\n### Final Output:\n\nYou need to generate 10 unique functions, each as per the code format.\n\n### Example of a Unique Function:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins