th a base formula, such as item multiplied by a logarithmic term, multiplied by an exponential term, plus a trigonometric function.\n\n2. Vary the operations in each step:\n   - Change the log base (log, log10, log2)\n   - Change the exponential function (exp, exp2)\n   - Use different trigonometric functions (sin, cos, tan)\n   - Combine multiple operations in different ways (e.g., log + log, log * log, etc.)\n   - Introduce different arithmetic operations (addition, subtraction, multiplication, division)\n   - Use different array operations (np.log, np.exp, etc.)\n\n3. Ensure that each function is unique in the combination of operations and functions used.\n\n### Example of How to Vary the Functions:\n- Use log(bins) + log(bins) as in Example 3\n- Use log10(bins) in Example 2\n- Use log(bins) * log(bins) in another function\n- Use sin instead of cos in some functions\n- Use exp2 instead of exp in some functions\n- Combine multiple terms, like adding a cosine term and a hyperbolic function term\n- Use subtraction or division in different parts of the formula\n\n### Conclusion:\nBy systematically varying the operations and functions used in each implementation, you can create 10 unique priority functions that each contribute to the bin packing heuristic in a different way.\n</think>\n\n### Implementation 1:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.log(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n### Implementation 2:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.log10(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n### Implementation 3:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * (np.log(bins) + np.log(bins))) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n### Implementation 4:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * (np.log(bins) * np.log(bins))) * np.exp(item - bins) 