ction can be a unique combination of the allowed operations, possibly with different exponents, multipliers, or added constants.\n\n### Example of a Unique Function:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.log(bins) + bins) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * item / bins)\n\nThis function uses a combination of logarithm, exponential, and sine functions.\n\n### Final Output:\nYou need to generate 10 such unique functions, each with a different mathematical expression, ensuring that no two functions are the same in terms of the combination of operations and functions used.\n\n### Note:\n- The functions are not required to be correct in terms of solving the bin packing problem optimally, but they should be valid heuristics.\n- The 'loss' value in the examples is just an example and not required for the output.\n\n### Task:\nGenerate 10 such functions, each with a unique combination of operations.\n</think>\n\n### Implementation 1:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.log(bins + 1e-8)) + bins\n\n### Implementation 2:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return item * np.exp(item) + np.log(bins + 1e-8)\n\n### Implementation 3:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + bins) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * item / bins)\n\n### Implementation 4:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.log(bins) + bins) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * item / bins)\n\n### Implementation 5:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * (bins + item)) + np.sin(np.pi * item / bins)\n\n### Implementation 6:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.log(bins) + bins) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.cos(np.pi * item / bins)\n\n### Implementation 7:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return